    parentName: "p"
  }, "Chinese Glazes"), ", Tichane approaches the subject from the perspective of a glaze chemist and gains valuable insight into the nature of blue celadons. \xA0Through testing, Tichane arrives at two formulas. \xA0The \u201C532.1\u201D formula contains\xA050 parts feldspar, 30 parts silica, 20 parts limestone, and 1 part iron oxide. \xA0The \u201C5321.1\u201D formula is the same but\xA0adds 10 parts kaolin. \xA0The type of kaolin added greatly affects the color of the glaze, for blue celadons a kaolin very low in titania such as Grolleg or New Zealand Halloysite is required."), mdx("p", null, "Below on the left is Tichane\u2019s 532.1 formula with 1% yellow iron oxide (YIO). \xA0On the right is the same formula but with Wollastonite instead of Whiting (of course this adds some silica to the mix). \xA0These tests were fired in a public kiln, temperature is uncertain but at least Orton cone 12, I believe Tichane\u2019s tests were fired to cone 10."), mdx("p", null, mdx("img", _extends({
